[{"short_id":"cpyxnw","created_at":"2026-06-08T08:33:45.000-05:00","title":"I wish Deno would keep doing what it does best","url":"https://hackers.pub/@hongminhee/2026/i-wish-deno-would-keep-doing-what-it-does-best","score":4,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"hongminhee","user_is_author":true,"tags":["javascript"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/cpyxnw","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/cpyxnw/i_wish_deno_would_keep_doing_what_it_does"},{"short_id":"q3gqcs","created_at":"2026-06-08T08:13:16.000-05:00","title":"Release Fil-C Linux/x86_64 version 0.679 · pizlonator/fil-c","url":"https://github.com/pizlonator/fil-c/releases/tag/v0.679","score":5,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"lollipopman","user_is_author":false,"tags":["c","release"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/q3gqcs","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/q3gqcs/release_fil_c_linux_x86_64_version_0_679"},{"short_id":"bqjxzj","created_at":"2026-06-08T07:24:26.000-05:00","title":"svg-line: Better Status Bars for Emacs","url":"https://www.chiply.dev/post-svg-line","score":4,"flags":1,"comment_count":3,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"chiply","user_is_author":true,"tags":["emacs"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/bqjxzj","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/bqjxzj/svg_line_better_status_bars_for_emacs"},{"short_id":"8hiogg","created_at":"2026-06-08T07:20:23.000-05:00","title":"HTMX Is So Cool I Rolled My Own","url":"https://dbushell.com/2024/04/16/htmx-and-modern-javascript/","score":11,"flags":0,"comment_count":2,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"FedericoSchonborn","user_is_author":false,"tags":["javascript","web"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/8hiogg","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/8hiogg/htmx_is_so_cool_i_rolled_my_own"},{"short_id":"bvtpjq","created_at":"2026-06-08T05:58:27.000-05:00","title":"The EU Open Source Strategy","url":"https://digital-strategy.ec.europa.eu/en/policies/open-source-strategy","score":7,"flags":1,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"linkdd","user_is_author":false,"tags":["culture"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/bvtpjq","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/bvtpjq/eu_open_source_strategy"},{"short_id":"lurkvp","created_at":"2026-06-08T05:07:25.000-05:00","title":"zalloc: Use zig allocators in your c code","url":"https://github.com/D-Berg/zalloc","score":5,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"hawski","user_is_author":false,"tags":["c","zig"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/lurkvp","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/lurkvp/zalloc_use_zig_allocators_your_c_code"},{"short_id":"i7moeh","created_at":"2026-06-08T04:49:21.000-05:00","title":"A fast, zero-copy Transit-format reader and writer written in C","url":"https://github.com/DotFox/transit.c","score":3,"flags":1,"comment_count":0,"description":"\u003cstrong\u003eWhat is Transit?\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://github.com/cognitect/transit-format\" rel=\"ugc\"\u003eTransit\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e is a format and a set of libraries for conveying values between applications written in different languages. It is layered on top of JSON and MessagePack, so you get their tooling and speed, but with a much richer type system and built-in payload compression. Think of it as \"JSON that round-trips real types\":\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003eGround types from the host format\u003c/strong\u003e: maps, arrays, strings, numbers, booleans, null\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003eExtension types JSON lacks\u003c/strong\u003e: keywords \u003ccode\u003e:foo\u003c/code\u003e, symbols, instants (timestamps), UUIDs, URIs, big integers/decimals, characters, byte arrays, sets, and lists\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003eBuilt-in compression (caching)\u003c/strong\u003e: repeated map keys, keywords, symbols, and tags are written once and then referenced by a short \u003ccode\u003e^N\u003c/code\u003e code, so verbose, key-heavy payloads shrink dramatically\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003eExtensible via tagged values\u003c/strong\u003e: ship your own types over the wire with a tag plus a representation, and decode them with a custom handler — no more \u003ccode\u003e{\"__type\": \"Date\", \"value\": \"...\"}\u003c/code\u003e hacks\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003eLanguage-agnostic \u0026amp; self-describing\u003c/strong\u003e: originally from Cognitect/Clojure, with implementations across many languages\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLearn more:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ca href=\"https://github.com/cognitect/transit-format\" rel=\"ugc\"\u003eOfficial Transit specification\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"## What is Transit?\r\n\r\n**[Transit](https://github.com/cognitect/transit-format)** is a format and a set of libraries for conveying values between applications written in different languages. It is layered on top of JSON and MessagePack, so you get their tooling and speed, but with a much richer type system and built-in payload compression. Think of it as \"JSON that round-trips real types\":\r\n\r\n- **Ground types from the host format**: maps, arrays, strings, numbers, booleans, null\r\n- **Extension types JSON lacks**: keywords `:foo`, symbols, instants (timestamps), UUIDs, URIs, big integers/decimals, characters, byte arrays, sets, and lists\r\n- **Built-in compression (caching)**: repeated map keys, keywords, symbols, and tags are written once and then referenced by a short `^N` code, so verbose, key-heavy payloads shrink dramatically\r\n- **Extensible via tagged values**: ship your own types over the wire with a tag plus a representation, and decode them with a custom handler — no more `{\"__type\": \"Date\", \"value\": \"...\"}` hacks\r\n- **Language-agnostic \u0026 self-describing**: originally from Cognitect/Clojure, with implementations across many languages\r\n\r\n**Learn more:** [Official Transit specification](https://github.com/cognitect/transit-format)","submitter_user":"delaguardo","user_is_author":true,"tags":["c","clojure"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/i7moeh","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/i7moeh/fast_zero_copy_transit_format_reader"},{"short_id":"tvppr8","created_at":"2026-06-08T04:36:56.000-05:00","title":"Using JSLint For Evil (2011, 2m44s)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-hCimLnIsDA","score":1,"flags":0,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"dzwdz","user_is_author":false,"tags":["law","video"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/tvppr8","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/tvppr8/using_jslint_for_evil_2011_2m44s"},{"short_id":"tb1itv","created_at":"2026-06-08T04:28:22.000-05:00","title":"Framework Laptop 13 Pro Deep Dive - LPCAMM2","url":"https://frame.work/gb/en/blog/framework-laptop-13-pro-deep-dive-lpcamm2","score":-1,"flags":2,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"watbe","user_is_author":false,"tags":["hardware"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/tb1itv","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/tb1itv/framework_laptop_13_pro_deep_dive_lpcamm2"},{"short_id":"yiwcln","created_at":"2026-06-08T04:23:20.000-05:00","title":"What are you doing this week?","url":"","score":6,"flags":0,"comment_count":7,"description":"\u003cp\u003eWhat are you doing this week? Feel free to share!\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eKeep in mind it’s OK to do nothing at all, too.\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"What are you doing this week? Feel free to share!\r\n\r\nKeep in mind it’s OK to do nothing at all, too.","submitter_user":"caius","user_is_author":true,"tags":["ask","programming"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/yiwcln","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/yiwcln/what_are_you_doing